content:
You can add the functionality of displaying real-time change on the meter scale values as the user slides it by adding an event listener for the 'input' or 'change' event to your slider.

Modify the 'range' input field and the addEventListener() invocation in your JavaScript as follows.

Here is the HTML:

```html
<div class="container">
  <h1>How was your day? 🤔</h1>
  <input type="range" min="0" max="10" value="5" class="slider" id="slider">
  <p id="slider-value">5</p>
  <button id="get-value">Submit</button>
  <p id="output"></p>
</div>
```

Then in your JavaScript:

```javascript
const slider = document.querySelector('#slider');
const sliderValue = document.querySelector('#slider-value');
const output = document.querySelector('#output');

slider.oninput = function() {
  sliderValue.textContent = this.value;
}

document.querySelector('#get-value').addEventListener('click', function() {
    const value = slider.value;  
    switch(value) {
        case '0':
            output.innerText = "You chose 0!";
            break;
        case '1':
            output.innerText = "You chose 1!";
            break;
        // continue for the rest of the numbers...
        case '10':
            output.innerText = "You chose 10!";
            break;
        default:
            output.innerText = `You chose ${value}!`;
    }
});
```

Now, as you move the slider, the value displayed on the meter will update in real-time. When the user submits, your switch-case statement will generate a message based on the current selected value.
